'''English'''  
In the age of artificial intelligence, the significance of Gödel–Escher–Bach (GEB) lies in the fundamental insight that human consciousness and creativity cannot be exhaustively accounted for by mere computational procedures or by the accumulation and processing of data. Today’s generative AI distills statistical regularities from vast datasets about the world to produce language, images, and music, yet it remains confined to “mechanical transformation within a formal system.” By contrast, Gödel’s incompleteness theorems show that in any sufficiently expressive formal system there are true statements that cannot be proven within the system, while Escher’s drawings and Bach’s music realize recursive, self-referential structures that obey rules even as they play at—and cross—their edges. This line of thought reveals that the distinctly human process of meaning-making, arising from self-referential loops and layered contexts, cannot be fully replicated by AI; hence, however sophisticated AI becomes, it is unlikely to instantiate consciousness or self-reflection in a human-like way.  

Alongside this, the ''Riemann Hypothesis''—still unproven at the heart of number theory—concerns the fine structure of the distribution of prime numbers via the zeros of the Riemann zeta function. Its stubborn resistance to proof, and the way it binds analytic form to arithmetic complexity, remind us that pattern is not explanation and statistical fit is not proof. For pattern-extracting AI systems, the hypothesis functions as an intellectual breakwater: a marker where empirical regularities meet deep mathematical structure that has not yet yielded to algorithmic methods. Whether it is ultimately proved or refuted, it stands with Gödel’s incompleteness and with Escher’s and Bach’s recursive art and music to outline a map of understanding whose frontier cannot be flattened into computation alone; it guides the design of complementary human–machine creativity and safeguards the uniqueness and irreducibility of human thought within technological civilization.  

